Download a few csv's¶

  • Stay At home table (unused, dates where Stay at home went into effect)
  • Region Table (What states are in the northeast, south, west, and midwest)

Merge in all data sources and add new fields¶

In [15]:
full_df = pd.merge(state_df, region_df, left_on=['state'], right_on=['State'])
full_df = pd.merge(full_df, pop_df, left_on=['state'], right_on=['STNAME'])
full_df = pd.merge(full_df, area_df)
full_df = pd.merge(full_df, stay_df)
full_df["date"] = pd.to_datetime(full_df['date']).dt.strftime('%m/%d/%Y')
full_df["sah_order_date"] = pd.to_datetime(full_df['sah_order_date']).dt.strftime('%m/%d/%Y')
In [16]:
# Get Mortality Rate/Case Density/State Density
full_df['mortality'] = 100 * full_df['deaths'] / (full_df['cases'] + 1)
full_df['case_density'] = 100 * full_df['cases'] / full_df['CENSUS2010POP']
full_df['state_density'] = full_df['CENSUS2010POP'] / full_df['area (sq. mi)']
In [17]:
# Plotly is sort of annoying. All regions need same start date
first_date = full_df['date'].min()

for region in full_df['Region'].unique():
    temp_df = full_df.loc[full_df['Region']==region]
    
    if not temp_df['date'].isin([first_date]).any():
        temp_row = temp_df.iloc[0]
        temp_row['date'] = first_date
        temp_row['cases'] = 0
        temp_row['deaths'] = 0
        full_df = full_df.append(temp_row)

full_df = full_df.sort_values(by='date')
In [18]:
# Get new cases / deaths per day
full_df['new_cases'] = 0
full_df['new_deaths'] = 0

for state in full_df['state'].unique():
    state_idx = full_df['state'] == state
    full_df['new_cases'].loc[state_idx] = full_df['cases'].loc[state_idx].diff()
    full_df['new_deaths'].loc[state_idx] = full_df['deaths'].loc[state_idx].diff()

full_df['new_cases'].fillna(value=0, inplace=True)
full_df['new_deaths'].fillna(value=0, inplace=True)

# Interestingly, there are a new points where cases/deaths go down... Set to zero to make log work
change_cases_idx = full_df['new_cases'] < 0
full_df['new_cases'].loc[change_cases_idx] = 0

change_deaths_idx = full_df['new_deaths'] < 0
full_df['new_deaths'].loc[change_deaths_idx] = 0

print('Number of updated cases: {}'.format(sum(change_cases_idx)))
print('Number of updated deaths: {}'.format(sum(change_deaths_idx)))

Number of updated cases: 1
Number of updated deaths: 3

So many fancy plots, so little time¶

  • First something general, mortality / number of cases over time for each state.
  • Bubble size indicates number of overall deaths
In [22]:
fig = px.scatter(full_df, y=full_df['mortality'],
                    x= full_df["cases"]+1,
                    range_y = [-0.05,full_df['mortality'].max()],
                    range_x = [1, full_df["cases"].max()+10000],
                    color= "Region", hover_name="state",
                    hover_data=["cases","deaths"],
                    range_color= [0, max(np.power(full_df["cases"],0.3))], 
                    animation_frame="date", 
                    animation_group="state",
                    color_continuous_scale=px.colors.sequential.Plasma,
                    title='COVID-19: Mortality Rate vs Total cases',
                    size = np.power(full_df["deaths"]+1,0.3)-0.5,
                    size_max = 30,
                    height =700,
                    log_x=True,
                    )
fig.update_coloraxes(colorscale="hot")
fig.update(layout_coloraxis_showscale=False)
fig.update_xaxes(title_text="Confirmed Cases (Log Scale)")
fig.update_yaxes(title_text="Mortality Rate (%)")
fig.show()

Word of warning, this only shows the mortality rate amoung confirmed cases. This is too high and needs also include the large amount of people going untested.
